{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512043"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:49:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11835"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11835"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.15,0.19,0.09,0.47]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4436"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43687"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4436"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"89"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1717"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43687"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department complaining of a sudden loss of vision in her right eye. Over the last two weeks she has been experiencing pain when combing her hair and pain on chewing her food. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings is most likely to be seen on fundus examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dot blot haemorrhages","Flame-shaped haemorrhages","Elevation of the retina with subretinal fluid","Neovascularisation of the disc","Cherry red spot"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is one of the classic presentations of giant cell arteritis (GCA). Loss of vision in this eye is unfortunately unlikely to recover. GCA is associated with arterial occlusion of branches of the ophthalmic artery. The ophthalmic artery supplies the choroidal circulation via the posterior ciliary arteries and in this case, the central retinal artery, which is why the classic\u003Cstrong\u003E cherry red spot\u003C/strong\u003E sign can be seen. What is described as a \u0022cherry red spot\u0022 refers to the relatively dark colour of the fovea (cherry) on a background of an oedematous and whitish-looking retina due to infarction of the arterial supply of the retina. Here is an example (Image 1).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt should be noted that although this is a classic sign of arterial occlusion, it may not be present in all cases or it may have not fully developed at the time of presentation. It is important to still treat the patient appropriately in cases where the clinical suspicion is very high. In such cases, the diagnosis is confirmed with a temporal artery biopsy. Central retinal artery occlusion could be confirmed with a fluorescein angiography, which probably will show delayed or absent choroidal circulation if any posterior ciliary arteries are also affected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst GCA can present with a CRA occlusion, it more often presents with arteritic anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy (A-AION) due to occlusion of posterior ciliary arteries that supply the optic disc and adjacent optic nerve. The fundal signs are a very pale swollen optic disc in a usually blind eye with no cherry red spot. Here is an example (Image 2). Rarely A-AION and CRA occur together.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlame-shaped haemorrhages \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E dot blot haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in retinal vascular disorders such as diabetic or hypertensive retinopathy. It may also be present in select inflammatory cases but less commonly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetinal elevation with subretinal fluid\u003C/strong\u003E is a description of retina detachment and is not a finding typically seen in vascular retinal disorders\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeovascularisation of the disc (NVD)\u003C/strong\u003E is the development of frail abnormal blood vessels on or around the optic disc. It occurs in response to increased production of vascular endothelial growth factors in the setting of chronic ischaemia in the retina. Examples of such cases are proliferative diabetic retinopathy, as a complication of central or branch retinal vein occlusion, or less commonly, CRA. NVDs are not seen in the acute stage of these diseases as it takes time for this process to manifest, it is rather a sign of chronic or longstanding ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Giant cell arteritis is associated with central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO).","Cherry red spot is a sign of central retinal artery occlusion (CRAO)."],"references":["Younger DS. Giant Cell Arteritis. Neurol Cli 2019; 37:335-44."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11835"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15798"},{"type":"media","id":"15799"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15798"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/stor